greek.definition: the first letter of the alphabet; figuratively, only (from its use as a numeral) first
greek.usage: Of Hebrew origin; the first letter of the alphabet; figuratively, only (from its use as a numeral) first: - Alpha.
Of Hebrew origin [Aharon]; Aaron, the brother of Moses: - Aaron.
Of Chaldee origin [ab]; father (as a vocative case): - Abba.

greek.definition: not to be trodden, i.e. impassable
greek.usage: From a (as a negative particle) and a derivative of baino; not to be trodden, i.e. impassable: - that cannot be trodden.
Of Chaldee origin [ab]; father (as a vocative): - Abba.
Of Hebrew origin; Abde, an Israelite: - Abde.
Of Hebrew origin; Abdiu, an Israelite: - Abdiu.
Of Hebrew origin [Abiyah]; Abia, an Israelite: - Abia.
Of Hebrew origin [Ebyathar]; Abiathar, an Israelite: - Abiathar.
Of foreign origin [compare Abil]; Abilene, a region in Syria: - Abilene.
Of Hebrew origin [Abihud]; Abiud, an Israelite: - Abiud.
From a (as a negative particle) and a variation of bathus; depthless, i.e. (specially) (infernal) "abyss": - deep, (bottomless) pit.
Of Hebrew origin [compare Agab]; Agabus, an Israelite: - Agabus.
From agathos and the base of ergon; to work good: - do good.

greek.definition: to be a well-doer (as a favor or a duty)
greek.usage: From agathopoios; to be a well-doer (as a favor or a duty): - (when) do good (well).
From agathopoios; well-doing, i.e. virtue: - well-doing.
From agathos and poieo; a well-doer, i.e. virtuous: - them that do well.

greek.definition: good (in any sense, often as a noun)
greek.usage: A primary word; "good" (in any sense, often as a noun): - benefit, good(-s, things), well.
From agathos; goodness, i.e. virtue or beneficence: - goodness.
From agalliao; exultation; specially, welcome: - gladness, (exceeding) joy.

greek.definition: to jump for joy, i.e. exult
greek.usage: From agan (much) and hallomai (to leap); properly, to jump for joy, i.e. exult: - be (exceeding) glad, with exceeding joy, rejoice (greatly).
From a (as a negative particle) and gamos; unmarried: - unmarried.

greek.definition: to be greatly afflicted, i.e. (figuratively) indignant
greek.usage: From agan (much) and achthos (grief; akin to the base of agkale); to be greatly afflicted, i.e. (figuratively) indignant: - be much (sore) displeased, have (be moved with, with) indignation.
From aganakteo; indignation: - indignation.

greek.definition: to love (in a social or moral sense)
greek.usage: From agape; to love (in a social or moral sense): - (be-) love(-ed).

greek.definition: love, i.e. affection or benevolence; specially (plural) a love-feast
greek.usage: From agapao; love, i.e. affection or benevolence; specially (plural) a love-feast: - (feast of) charity(-ably), dear, love.
From agapao; beloved: - (dearly, well) beloved, dear.
Of Hebrew origin [Hagar]; Hagar, the concubine of Abraham: - Hagar.

greek.definition: to be a courier, i.e. (by implication) to press into public service
greek.usage: Of foreign origin [compare aggar]; to be a courier, i.e. (by implication) to press into public service: - compel (to go) unto, press.
From aggos (a pail, perhaps as bent; compare the base of agkale); a receptacle: - vessel.
From agello; an announcement, i.e. (by implication) precept: - message.

greek.definition: a messenger; especially an "angel"; by implication, a pastor
greek.usage: From aggello [probably derived from agoo; compare agele] (to bring tidings); a messenger; especially an "angel"; by implication, a pastor: - angel, messenger.
From agoo (compare agele); a drove: - herd.
From a (as negative particle) and genetos (born); unborn, i.e. in perpetual infancy: - unbegotten.
From a (as negative particle) and genealogeo; unregistered as to genealogy: - without genealogy.

greek.definition: properly, without kin, i.e. (of unknown descent, and by implication) ignoble
greek.usage: From a (as negative particle) and genos; properly, without kin, i.e. (of unknown descent, and by implication) ignoble: - base things.

greek.definition: to make holy, i.e. (ceremonially) purify or consecrate; (mentally) to venerate
greek.usage: From hagios; to make holy, i.e. (ceremonially) purify or consecrate; (mentally) to venerate: - hallow, be holy, sanctify.

greek.definition: purification, i.e. (the state) purity; concretely (by Hebraism) a purifier
greek.usage: From hagiazō; purification, i.e. (the state) purity; concretely (by Hebraism) a purifier: - holiness, sanctification.

greek.definition: sacred (physically, pure, morally blameless or religious, ceremonially, consecrated)
greek.usage: From hagos (an awful thing) [compare agno, hagnos]; sacred (physically, pure, morally blameless or religious, ceremonially, consecrated): - (most) holy (one, thing), saint.

greek.definition: sacred (physically, pure, morally blameless or religious, ceremonially, consecrated)
greek.usage: From hagos (an awful thing) [compare agno, hagnos]; sacred (physically, pure, morally blameless or religious, ceremonially, consecrated): - (most) holy (one, thing), saint.

hebrew.definition: father, in a literal and immediate, or figurative and remote application
hebrew.usage: A primitive word; father, in a literal and immediate, or figurative and remote application): - chief, (fore-)father(-less), X patrimony, principal.

hebrew.definition: father, in a literal and immediate, or figurative and remote application
hebrew.usage: A primitive word; father, in a literal and immediate, or figurative and remote application): - chief, (fore-)father(-less), X patrimony, principal.
From the same as 'ab; a green plant: - greenness, fruit.
From the same as 'ab; fruit (in a wide sense): - fruit.

hebrew.definition: Abagtha, one of the seven eunuchs of Ahasuerus
hebrew.usage: Of foreign origin; Abagtha, one of the seven eunuchs of Ahasuerus: - Abagtha.

hebrew.definition: properly, to wander away, i.e. lose oneself; by implication to perish (causative, destroy)
hebrew.usage: A primitive root; properly, to wander away, i.e. lose oneself; by implication to perish (causative, destroy): - break, destroy(-uction), + not escape, fail, lose, (cause to, make) perish, spend, X and surely, take, be undone, X utterly, be void of, have no way to flee.
Of Hebrew origin; Abaddon, an Israelite: - Abaddon.
Active of abad; a perishing; ruin: - destruction.

hebrew.definition: concrete, something lost; abstract, destruction, i.e. Hades
hebrew.usage: From abad; concrete, something lost; abstract, destruction, i.e. Hades: - lost. Compare abaddon.

hebrew.definition: Abagtha, one of the seven eunuchs of Ahasuerus
hebrew.usage: Of foreign origin; Abagtha, one of the seven eunuchs of Ahasuerus: - Abagtha.
Of Hebrew origin; Abaddon, an Israelite: - Abaddon.
From abad; a perishing: - destruction.
From abad; a perishing; concretely, Hades: - destruction.

hebrew.definition: to breathe after, i.e. (figuratively) to crave
hebrew.usage: A primitive root; to breathe after, i.e. (figuratively) to crave: - desire.
From abah; want: - desire.
From an unused root (meaning to be yellow); ebeh, a species of gall-insect: - ebah.
Dual of a primitive word; Abajim, an Israelite: - Abajim.
From the same as 'ab; a manger or stall: - crib.
From an unused root (apparently meaning to turn); an outburst of passion: - rage.
From an unused root (apparently meaning to turn); an outburst of passion: - rage.
From 'ab; fatherly; Abi, Hezekiah's mother: - Abi.

hebrew.definition: Abiel, the name of two Israelites
hebrew.usage: From 'ab and 'el; father (i.e. source) of God; Abiel, the name of two Israelites: - Abiel.
From 'ab and 'acaph; father of gathering (i.e. gatherer); Abiasaph, an Israelite: - Abiasaph.

hebrew.definition: green, i.e. a young ear of grain; hence, the name of the month Abib or Nisan
hebrew.usage: From an unused root (meaning to be tender); green, i.e. a young ear of grain; hence, the name of the month Abib or Nisan: - Abib, ear, green ears of corn (not maize).
From 'ab and Gibon; father (i.e. founder) of Gibon; Abi-Gibon, perhaps an Israelite: - father of Gibeon.

hebrew.definition: Abigal or Abigail, the name of two Israelitesses
hebrew.usage: Feminine of 'ab and gil; father of joy; Abigail or Abigal, the name of two Israelitesses: - Abigail.
From 'ab and dan; father of judgment; Abidan, an Israelite: - Abidan.
From 'ab and dan; father of judgment; Abidan, an Israelite: - Abidan.

hebrew.definition: Abiah, the name of two Israelites
hebrew.usage: From 'ab and Yahh; father of (i.e. worshipper of) Jah; Abijah, the name of several Israelites: - Abiah, Abijah.
From 'ab and hu'; father of him (i.e. worshipper); Abihu, a son of Aaron: - Abihu.
From 'ab and hod; father of renown; Abihud, an Israelite: - Abihud.

hebrew.definition: Abihail, the name of three Israelites
hebrew.usage: From 'ab and chayil; father of might; Abihail or Abichail, the name of three Israelites: - Abihail.
From 'ab and the active participle of azar with the article interposed; father of the help; Abi-ha-Ezri, an Israelite: - Abi-ezrite.
From 'ab and yoneh; father of poverty (i.e. unfortunate); Abiyon, an Israelite: - Abion.
Patronymic from Abiyon; an Abionite or descendant of Abion: - Abionite.
From 'ab and noam; father of pleasantness (i.e. gracious); Abinoam, an Israelite: - Abinoam.
From 'ab and 'Albon with the article inserted; father of Albon; Abi-Albon, an Israelite: - Abi-albon.
From 'ab and 'Ashan; father of Ashan; Abi-Ashan, an Israelite: - Abi-ashan.
From 'ab and ezer; father of help (i.e. helpful); Abi-Ezer, an Israelite: - Abi-ezer.

hebrew.definition: Abiezer, the name of two Israelites
hebrew.usage: From 'ab and ezer; father of help (i.e. helpful); Abiezer, the name of two Israelites: - Abiezer.
